'''ATI Radeon''' is a brand of [[graphics processing unit]]s (GPU) that since [[2000]] has been manufactured by [[ATI Technologies]] and subsequently [[AMD]] and is the successor to their [[ATI Rage|Rage]] line. There are four different groups, which can be differentiated by the [[DirectX]] generation they support.  More specific distinctions can also be followed, such as the [[HyperZ]] version, the number of [[Pipeline (computing)|pixel pipeline]]s, and of course, the [[Computer storage|memory]] and [[Central processing unit|processor]] [[clock speed]]s.

==ATI Radeon Processor Generations==
{| class="wikitable" style="margin: 1em auto 1em auto"
|-
! rowspan=2 | Series
! colspan=2 | Graphics [[Application programming interface|API]]s support
! rowspan=2 | Notes
|-
! width="85pt"| DirectX
! width="85pt"| OpenGL
|-
| '''[[Radeon R100|R100]]'''
| DirectX 7.0
| align="center"| [[OpenGL]] 1.3
| Was ATI's first graphics processor to be fully [[DirectX]] 7 compliant. It was first introduced in 2000. R100 brought with it large gains in bandwidth and fill-rate efficiency through the new [[HyperZ]] technology. Initial models included Radeon SDR, DDR and 7000/VE. The final release was the Radeon 7500.
|-
| '''[[Radeon R200|R200]]'''
| DirectX 8.1 
| align="center"| OpenGL 1.4
| ATI's second generation Radeon. This design included ATI's first programmable shader architecture and introduced pixel shader 1.4, the most advanced shader model prior to 2.0. This line includes Radeon 8500 - 9200, 9250.
|-
| '''[[Radeon R300|R300]]'''
| DirectX 9.0 
| rowspan = 4 align="center"| OpenGL 2.0
| ATI's breakthrough DirectX 9.0 technology, released in 2002, made ATI the technology leader for several years with its industry-leading pixel shader 2.0 performance. Included in this generation are Radeon 9500 - 9800, X300 - X600, X1050.
|-
| '''[[Radeon R420|R420]]'''
|  DirectX 9.0b
| While heavily based upon the previous generation, this line included extensions to the Shader Model 2 feature-set. Shader Model 2b, the specification ATI and Microsoft defined with this generation, offered somewhat more shader program flexibility. This generation's technology is used in Radeon X700 - X850.
|-
| '''[[Radeon R520|R520]]'''
| DirectX 9.0c
| ATI's DirectX 9.0c series of graphics cards, with complete [[shader|Shader Model 3.0]] support. Launched in October 2005, this series brought a number of enhancements including the floating point render target technology necessary for [[high dynamic range rendering|HDR rendering]] with [[anti-aliasing]]. Cards released include X1300 - X1950.
|-
| '''[[Radeon R600|R600]]'''
| DirectX 10.0/<br>DirectX 10.1 (RV670)
| ATI's first series of ATI Radeon GPUs supporting the [[Direct3D#Direct3D 10|Direct3D 10.0]] specification and the company's second graphics solution to employ [[Unified shader model|unified shader]] technology. Releases of this platform include the HD 2400, HD 2600 and HD 2900. There are also products supporting DirectX 10.1, known as the HD 3000 series, with a die shrink.
|-
| '''[[Radeon R700|R700]]'''
| DirectX 10.1
| align="center"| OpenGL 2.1
| ATI's new series, based on the R600 architecture. Mostly a bolstered card with many more stream processors, with improvements to power consumption and GDDR5 support for the high-end RV770 chip. It arrived in late June 2008. The HD 4850 and HD 4870 have 800 stream processors and GDDR3 and GDDR5 memory respectively.
|}

==Radeon Card Brands==
AMD does not actually sell Radeon cards at the retail level. Instead, it sells the hardware to 3rd party manufacturers who in turn sell their cards to the public. Examples of Radeon brands include Diamond Multimedia and Sapphire Technology

==Product naming scheme==
Since ATI's first DirectX 9-class GPU, the company has followed a naming scheme that relates each product to a market segment.

* <sup>1</sup> Stream Processors only applicable to Radeon HD 2000 series video cards.
